    <centralBlocks>
      <Value><![CDATA[[
  {
    "key": "9b0eda36-046a-4b99-ab13-1b2075043fe1",
    "name": "Why QMU?",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Why QMU?",
    "content": "<ul>\n<li>The course is taught by an experienced and dedicated team who are driven by a student-centred approach to learning and teaching.</li>\n</ul>"
  },
  {
    "key": "9ec78465-685e-441e-83f2-07f1de2785af",
    "name": "About the course",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "About the course",
    "content": "<p>Are you fascinated by human nature, by who we are and how we interact? Do you want to understand what impacts the shape of society around us and how it could be changed for the better? Then you will enjoy our joint course in psychology and sociology as it provides a challenging and stimulating environment for exploring these questions around the individual and society.</p>\n<p>In this course you will learn to use social scientific methods and evidence to make sense of human behaviour. You will learn how to think and write critically, giving you skills that can be valuable in many fields. You will be given opportunities to go into communities and apply your skills and knowledge in a real-world context and reflect upon the ways that psychological and sociological knowledge can effect real change in people’s everyday lives.</p>\n<p>The modules in Years One and Two will give you a thorough grounding in the key concepts, theories and schools of thought in psychology and sociology. You will look at the historical development and contemporary applications of psychological and sociological knowledge as well as explore the very latest debates in both disciplines. We know how important it is that you develop a wide range of transferable talents, so you will also focus on improving your interpersonal and presentation skills, effective reading and writing, analytical thinking and critical reflection, as well as your research skills.</p>\n<p>In Years Three and Four you will develop an in-depth understanding of a broad range of substantive debates within the disciplines of psychology and sociology: the psychology of risk, the origins and structure of memory and eyewitness testimony, the sociology of gender and sexuality, sociologies of liberation, and social interaction and social order. Working closely with a member of academic staff, you will conduct your own independent research project in Year Four, in which you will be encouraged to bring together your knowledge of academic theories and concepts, as well as refining your research skills.</p>\n<p>Your ability to understand the relationship between complex academic theory and practical research will certainly enhance your employability on completion of this course.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "141f5bdd-8641-4952-ac72-0dee90786ffc",
    "name": "Structure",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Structure",
    "content": "<p>You can opt to study for an honours degree over four years or an ordinary degree over three years. You will complete a range of modules each year as outlined.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "19684037-6fe8-4627-b9ae-172d31015555",
    "name": "Teaching, learning and assessment",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Teaching, learning and assessment",
    "content": "<p><span>You will be taught in lectures, seminars, practical workshops and laboratories. Outside these timetabled sessions you will be expected to continue learning through self-study. Your work will be assessed using a number of techniques, including essay writing, presentations, report writing, critical reflections and examinations. </span></p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "fd967918-6ef9-459c-a5c3-419a472e2c12",
    "name": "Modules",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Modules",
    "content": "<p><strong>Year One</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Introduction to Psychology 1</li>\n<li>Foundations of Psychology: Core Concepts and Practices</li>\n<li>Introduction to Academia</li>\n<li>The Sociological Imagination 1 – Classical and Contemporary Sociological Theories and Concepts</li>\n<li>Introduction to Psychology 2</li>\n<li>The Sociological Imagination 2 – Diversity, Identity and Wellbeing</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Year Two</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Social and Psychological Inquiry – Philosophy and Design</li>\n<li>Developmental and Social Psychology</li>\n<li>Current Debates in Sociology</li>\n<li>Sociology of Culture</li>\n<li>Self and Identity</li>\n<li>Individual Difference, Wellbeing and Ethical Practice</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Year Three</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sociology of Knowledge &amp; Science</li>\n<li>Research Design: Theory and Practice</li>\n<li>Interaction and Social Order</li>\n<li>Developmental Psychology</li>\n<li>Social Psychology and Social Movements</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Year Four</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dissertation (in Psychology, Sociology or both)</li>\n<li>two Sociology option modules</li>\n<li>two psychology option modules</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Sociology option modules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sociology of Liberation</li>\n<li>European Policy and Politics</li>\n<li>Queer Theory, Gender and Sexual Politics</li>\n<li>Gender Justice and Violence</li>\n<li>Feminist Approaches</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Psychology option modules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eyewitness Testimony</li>\n<li>Evolutionary Psychology</li>\n<li>Volunteering and Community Engagement</li>\n<li>Psychology of Pain</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The modules listed here are correct at time of posting (April 2021) but may differ slightly to those offered in 2022. Please check back here for any updates.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "d87e9955-5423-445c-90d5-d1e26858bc3c",
    "name": "Exchange opportunities",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Exchange opportunities",
    "content": "<p>In Year Two or Three you have the opportunity (where available) to study for one semester at a university overseas. For more information, visit <a href=\"http://www.qmu.ac.uk/study-here/international-students/exchanges-and-study-abroad/\">Exchanges and Study Abroad</a>.</p>\n<p>On December 24th 2020, the UK Government announced that as an outcome of Brexit negotiations, the United Kingdom would not be seeking to participate in the Erasmus+ successor programme.</p>\n<p>From 2022/23 Queen Margaret University will no longer operate under the Erasmus+ scheme. Over the coming year we will be working with new and existing partners on study abroad and exchange opportunities for the 2022/23 academic year and beyond.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "3560af6e-8b7c-4078-8d41-438847707119",
    "name": "Careers",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Careers",
    "content": "<p>You’ll graduate with a wide range of skills, knowledge and aptitudes. You’ll be ready to step out into a wide range of careers, to develop yourself in even greater ways. Our alumni are pursuing careers in social and community work, consumer and social research, public policy development, teaching, academia, marketing and human resource management. </p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "23efc503-7850-490e-8f57-907edb9c9898",
    "name": "Entry requirements",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Entry requirements",
    "content": "<p>Scottish Higher: Standard - BBCC, Minimum - BCCC</p>\n<p>A Level: CCD</p>\n<p>Irish Leaving Certificate: H3 H3 H3 H3</p>\n<p>International Baccalaureate: 26 points</p>\n<p>International: IELTS of 6.0 with no element lower than 5.5</p>\n<p>Required: English required at Nat 5/ GCSE</p>\n<p>Mature/Access: Visit our <a href=\"/study-here/access-to-higher-education/college-leavers-and-mature-students/\" title=\"College Leavers and Mature Students Advice\">College Leavers and Mature Students Advice page</a><span> for more information.</span></p>\n<p>We welcome applications from mature students with relevant qualifications and/or experience.</p>\n<p>Direct Entry:</p>\n<p><em>Year Two</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>HNC in a related subject with B in the graded unit</li>\n<li>Scottish Higher: BC at Advanced Higher in relevant subjects plus BB at Higher</li>\n<li>A Level: BBB in relevant subjects</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Year Three</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>HND in a related subject with CB in the graded units</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For details of related HNC and HND courses, visit our <a href=\"/study-here/access-to-higher-education/college-leavers-and-mature-students/\" title=\"College Leavers and Mature Students Advice\">College Leavers and Mature Students Advice page.</a></p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "080dfb5b-7234-4645-9c66-15e0561e003b",
    "name": "Associate student places",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Associate student places",
    "content": "<p>You can study this course as an associate student completing your first year at Newbattle Abbey College or West Lothian College.</p>\n<p>For more information, visit <a data-id=\"3964\" href=\"/{localLink:3964}\" title=\"Associate Student Scheme\">Associate Student Scheme</a>.<br /><br /><strong>Entry criteria for Associate students is CCC at Higher</strong></p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "40e417c5-4e60-44d0-a445-eda3a4abb9cb",
    "name": "Professional registration/accreditation",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Professional registration/accreditation",
    "content": "<p>Successful completion of this degree does not confer Graduate Basis for Chartered Membership (GBC) that enables access to professional training as a Chartered Psychologist.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "5445dae5-011b-405d-94f9-bbdd2c96e553",
    "name": "Teaching staff, class sizes and timetables",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Teaching staff, class sizes and timetables",
    "content": "<p>For more information, please visit ‘<a href=\"/study-here/undergraduate-study/undergraduate-subject-overviews/how-we-teach-and-how-youll-learn-undergraduate/\">How we teach and how you’ll learn’</a>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "d1970b58-bfa8-4b5a-aed6-cd6d355fa3a6",
    "name": "Awarding body",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Awarding body",
    "content": "<p>QMU. More information is in the ‘External Review’ section of our ‘<a href=\"/study-here/undergraduate-study/undergraduate-subject-overviews/how-we-teach-and-how-youll-learn-undergraduate/\">How we teach and how you’ll learn’</a> page.</p>"
  }
]]]></Value>
